section.para:
This is the main class. Its initial implementation followed the one presented by Jonathan Richard Shewchuk in Triangle: A &TRI; instance contains references to its three vertices
public Vertex [] vertex = new Vertex[3]; private Object [] adj = new Object[3]; private int groupId = -1;
A &TRI; contains three references to its vertices, and three references to adjacent triangles. The adj instance variable is of type Object instead of &TRI; in order to handle non-manifold objects; each element then contains a list of triangles. The groupId instance variable contains the identifier of a shell.

Algorithms do often need to compute lists of triangles.  In order to
avoid allocation of these lists, a singly linked list is provided by
this class.  It uses class variables, so only one list can be active at
any time.  Here is an example:

     //  Begin a new list
     Triangle.listLock();
     ...
     //  In a loop, add triangles to this list.
       tri.listCollect();
     //  Check whether a triangle is contained in this list.
     //  This is very fast because it tests if its link pointer
     //  is null or not.
       if (tri.isListed()) {
          ...
       }
     //  Loop over collected triangles.
     for (Iterator it = Triangle.getTriangleListIterator(); it.hasNext(); )
     {
       Triangle t = (Triangle) it.next();
       ...
     }
     //  When finished, remove all links between triangles
     Triangle.listRelease();


New elements are added at the end of the list so that
listCollect can be called while
getTriangleListIterator is in action.

An &OTRI; instance is a handle on an half-edge.
Its instance variables are:

        Triangle tri;
        int localNumber;
        int attributes;

Once it is created, its members are updated when traversing mesh.
Symmetric edges are retrieved through tri.adj
and tri.adjPos.

There are accessors for the first two instance variables:

        public final Triangle getTri()
        public final int getLocalNumber()

These variables cannot be set directly, but

        public final void bind(Triangle t, int l)

does the same thing.  The reason why there are no setTri
and setLocalNumber methods is that setTri
would almost always be followed by a call to pullAttributes,
thus bind is a shortcut for these two calls.

public final void contract(Vertex n)
V1 V1 V3+-------+-------+ V4 V3 +------+------+ V4 \ t3 / \ t4 / \ t3 | t4 / \ / \ / \ | / \ / t1 \ / \ | / o +-------+ d ------> n + / \ t2 / \ / | \ / \ / \ / | \ / t5 \ / t6 \ / t5 | t6 \ +-------+-------+ +------+------+ V5 V2 V6 V5 V2 V6
Contract an edge. Two triangles are removed, and all adjacent triangles are updated to replace &o; and &d; vertices by &n;. The following method
public final boolean canContract(Vertex n)
must be called before contract(Vertex n) to check that this contraction is valid.

public final void split(Vertex n)
V1 V1 + /|\ / \ / | \ / \ / t1 | t3 \ / t1 \ / | \ o +-------+ d ---> o +-------+-------+ d \ t2 / \ n| / \ / \ t2 | t4 / \ / \ | / + \|/ V2 V2
This is the opposite of contract.

The inner class QuadTree.Cell is defined like
this:

    protected class Cell
    {
        // Maximal number of vertices which can be stored in a cell.
        protected static final int BUCKETSIZE = 10;

        // Number of vertices stored below the current cell.
        protected int nItems = 0;

        // References to bound objects.
        protected Object [] subQuad = null;
    }

A QuadTree.Cell instance contains either vertices or four
children nodes (some of them may be null).  A cell
can contain at most QuadTree.Cell.BUCKETSIZE vertices
(default is 10).  By convention, nItems  is
positive if the cell contains vertices, and negative if it contains
children nodes.  Its absolute value is always the total number of
vertices located in this cell.
When a cell contains vertices and becomes full, it is splitted: children
nodes are created, vertices are stored there and the
subQuad instance variable contains references
to these children nodes.  On the contrary, when all vertices are removed
from a cell, it is deleted.  And when all children of a cell are empty,
this cell is removed.

Here is an example to collect inside a list all vertices stored in a
QuadTree q:

    class collectAllVerticesProcedure implements QuadTreeProcedure
    {
        protected ArrayList vertexList = new ArrayList();
        public final int action(Object o, int s, int i0, int j0)
        {
            Cell self = (Cell) o;
            if (self.nItems > 0)
            {
                for (int i = 0; i < self.nItems; i++)
                    vertexList.add(self.subQuad[i]);
            }
            return 0;
        }
    };
    collectAllVerticesProcedure cproc = new collectAllVerticesProcedure();
    q.walk(cproc);
    ArrayList vlist = cproc.vertexList;

Distances between vertices can be computed either in Euclidian 2D space, or
with a Riemannian metrics.  This is controlled by the
setCompGeom method.  Distances are computed in Euclidian 2D
space when its argument is an instance of
org.jcae.mesh.amibe.ds.tools.Calculus2D,
and in Riemannian metrics (see
org.jcae.mesh.amibe.metrics.Metric2D) when
it is an instance of
org.jcae.mesh.amibe.ds.tools.Calculus3D.
By default, distances are computed in Euclidian 2D space.

    //  Compute distances in getNearVertex and getNearestVertex
    //  with an Euclidian 2D metric
    q.setCompGeom(new org.jcae.mesh.amibe.ds.tools.Calculus2D());
    ...
    //  ... with a Riemannian 2D metric
    q.setCompGeom(new org.jcae.mesh.amibe.ds.tools.Calculus2D());

The inner class Octree.Cell is defined like
this:

    protected class Cell
    {
        // Number of vertices stored below the current cell.
        protected int nItems = 0;

        // References to bound objects.
        protected Object [] subOctree = null;
    }

An Octree.Cell instance contains either vertices
or eight children nodes (some of them may be null).
A cell can contain at most Octree.BUCKETSIZE
vertices (default is 10).  By convention,
nItems is positive if the cell contains
vertices, and negative if it contains children nodes.  Its absolute
value is always the total number of vertices located in this cell.
When a cell contains vertices and becomes full, it is splitted: children
nodes are created, vertices are stored there and the
subOctree instance variable contains references
to these children nodes.  On the contrary, when all vertices are removed
from a cell, it is deleted.  And when all children of a cell are empty,
this cell is removed.

Here is an example to collect inside a list all vertices stored in a
Octree oct:

    class collectAllVerticesProcedure implements OctreeProcedure
    {
        protected ArrayList vertexList = new ArrayList();
        public final int action(Object o, int s, int i0, int j0)
        {
            Cell self = (Cell) o;
            if (self.nItems > 0)
            {
                for (int i = 0; i < self.nItems; i++)
                    nodelist.add(self.subQuad[i]);
            }
            return 0;
        }
    };
    collectAllVerticesProcedure cproc = new collectAllVerticesProcedure();
    oct.walk(cproc);
    ArrayList vlist = cproc.vertexList;

Here are the most useful methods:


    public void insert(Object o, double value)
      Inserts the object o into
      the tree, associated to the quality factor
      value.


    public double remove(Object o)
      Removes this object from the tree.  Its old
      quality factor is returned.


    public void update(Object o, double value)
      Updates the quality factor of the specified
      object to a new value.


    public Object first()
    public Object last()
      Returns the Object with
      the lowest and highest quality factor.


    public Object prev()
    public Object next()
      After first or last
      methods are called, these methods return the
      Object immediately before or after the
      current one in the tree.

Example:

    PAVLSortedTree tree = new PAVLSortedTree();
    OTriangle ot = new OTriangle();
    // Insert triangle areas into the tree
    for (Iterator itf = mesh.getTriangles().iterator(); itf.hasNext(); )
    {
        Triangle f = (Triangle) itf.next();
        if (f.isOuter())
            continue;
        ot.bind(f);
        tree.insert(f, ot.computeArea());
    }
    // Process triangles according to their area in ascending order
    for (Object o = tree.first(); o != null; o = tree.next())
    {
        Triangle f = (Triangle) o;
        ...
    }

Example:
SmoothNodes3D smooth = new SmoothNodes3D(mesh, 20); smooth.compute();
The second parameter of the constructor is a number of iterations. Vertex smoothing needs indeed to be processed several times; this algorithm usually converges slowly. We need to adjust the number of iterations and the relaxation factor. TODO: the latter is currently hardwired to 0.1 into SmoothNodes3D.

Edges are sorted and splitted in turn, the longest edge being processed first. Example: if a mesh has already been performed with a target size of discr, the following commands will split edges longer then discr/2:
SplitEdge split = new SplitEdge(m, 0.5*discr); split.compute();
TODO: currently edges longer than sqrt(2)*discr/2 will be splitted.
